Reasoning: The paper discusses a bibliometric analysis of research performance by Italian universities, which involves the use of digital libraries and data mining techniques, suggesting a potential fit with the cs.DL (Digital Libraries) sub-category. The analysis also involves the use of statistical methods to assess the impact of policy interventions on research productivity, which could be relevant to the cs.CY (Computational Geometry) and cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper may be relevant to the cs.CE (Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science) sub-category, given the focus on productivity incentives and competition mechanisms in research institutions. Finally, the paper may also be relevant to the cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) sub-category, as it involves the analysis of sensitive data related to research performance.
